… as Kaduna extends sit-at-home by 30 days Nigerians are eagerly awaiting President Muhammadu Buhari’s briefing on the latest measures to be adopted in the fight against the spread of COVID-19 in Nigeria, as another two weeks of lockdown expires tomorrow (Monday). Lagos, Abuja and Kano have been on lockdown for four weeks as part of strict measures to ensure that the coronavirus cases don’t skyrocket to an unmanageable level. The Minister of Health, Dr. Osagie Ehanire; and the Director-General, Nigeria Centre for Disease Control, Dr. Chike Ihekweazu, briefed the President, on Sunday, on the next steps to take as the world still battles the COVID-19 pandemic. Buhari is expected to address the nation tomorrow (Monday). The government officials briefed the President just as Governor Nasir El-Rufai of Kaduna State extended the lockdown in his state by another 30 days. A statement on Sunday, signed by the media aide to the Governor, Muyiwa Adekeye, said the decision to extend the lockdown followed the recommendation of the State Standing Committee on COVID-19, chaired by the Deputy Governor, Dr Hadiza Balarabe. The lockdown extension, according to the statement, takes effect from Sunday, April 26, 2020, while the two-day window of relaxation of the restriction of movement (Tuesdays and Wednesdays), has been reduced to only one day (Wednesdays). 